### RefCell in Rust

`RefCell<T>` provides interior mutability - the ability to mutate data even when there are immutable references to it. Borrowing rules are enforced at runtime instead of compile time.

---

### Cell vs RefCell

| Feature | `Cell<T>` | `RefCell<T>` |
|---------|-----------|--------------|
| Types | Copy types only | Any type |
| Borrow check | No borrows (get/set) | Runtime borrow checking |
| Method | `get()`, `set()` | `borrow()`, `borrow_mut()` |
| Thread-safe | No | No |

---

### Examples

```rust
use std::cell::RefCell;

// Interior mutability pattern
struct Messenger {
    messages: RefCell<Vec<String>>,
}

impl Messenger {
    fn new() -> Self {
        Messenger {
            messages: RefCell::new(vec![]),
        }
    }

    fn send(&self, msg: &str) {
        self.messages.borrow_mut().push(String::from(msg));
        // self is &self, but we can mutate!
    }

    fn message_count(&self) -> usize {
        self.messages.borrow().len()
    }
}

// Runtime borrow checking
let cell = RefCell::new(5);
{
    let m1 = cell.borrow_mut();  // OK
    // let m2 = cell.borrow_mut();  // PANICS at runtime!
}
```

> **Key Point:** `RefCell` enforces borrowing rules at runtime. Violating the rules (e.g., two mutable borrows) causes a panic. Use `RefCell` when you need mutation in code that only has `&self` access. Combine with `Rc` for multiple owners with interior mutability.

codeExample:
use std::cell::RefCell;

fn main() {
    let data = RefCell::new(vec![1, 2, 3]);

    // Immutable reference to RefCell, but we can mutate the inner data
    {
        let mut borrowed = data.borrow_mut();
        borrowed.push(4);
        borrowed.push(5);
    }  // mutable borrow ends here

    println!("Data: {:?}", data.borrow());

    // Try to create two mutable borrows (will panic if both active)
    let mut ref1 = data.borrow_mut();
    // let mut ref2 = data.borrow_mut();  // PANICS at runtime
    ref1.push(6);
}
